  "prompt": "How can I learn jazz piano improvisation without a band?",
  "response": "Here are several ways to learn jazz piano improvisation on your own:\n\n1. Practice Techniques\n- Learn jazz scales (major, minor, blues, pentatonic)\n- Study chord progressions and voicings\n- Practice transcribing solos from recordings\n- Work on rhythmic variations and syncopation\n\n2. Learning Resources\n- Online video tutorials\n- Jazz piano method books\n- Instructional websites like JazzPianoSkills\n- YouTube channels dedicated to jazz improvisation\n\n3. Technology Aids\n- Use backing track apps and websites\n- Download MIDI backing tracks\n- Use software like iRealPro for chord progressions\n- Record and listen to your own improvisations\n\n4. Solo Practice Methods\n- Practice over standard jazz chord progressions\n- Play along with recorded jazz tracks\n- Use metronome to develop rhythmic sense\n- Improvise over ii-V-I progressions\n- Learn bebop and blues licks\n\n5. Ear Training\n- Listen to jazz pianists like Bill Evans, Herbie Hancock\n- Transcribe solos by ear\n- Practice identifying chord progressions\n- Develop melodic language through active listening\n\n6. Online Courses\n- Coursera\n- Udemy\n- MasterClass jazz piano courses\n\nConsistent practice and focused listening are key to developing jazz improvisation skills.",
